TY  - JOUR
T1  - Multilateral Contracting with Externalities
AU  - Gomes, Armando
Y1  - 2005/07/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2005.00617.x
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1329
EP  - 1350
VL  - 73
IS  - 4
KW  - Contracts
KW  - externalities
KW  - renegotiation
KW  - coalitional bargaining
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2005.00617.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper proposes a model for multilateral contracting, where contracts are written and renegotiated over time, and where contracts may impose externalities on other agents. Equilibria always exist and the equilibrium value function is linear and monotonically increasing on the contracts. If the grand coalition, or contracting among all agents, is inefficient, we show that bargaining delays arise in positive-externality games and equilibrium inefficiency may remain bounded away from zero even as bargaining frictions converge to zero. Otherwise, if the grand coalition is efficient, there are no bargaining delays, convergence to the grand coalition occurs in a finite number of contracting rounds, and the outcome becomes efficient as players become more patient.
ER  - 

