TY  - JOUR
T1  - Uncovering the Distribution of Motorists' Preferences for Travel Time and Reliability
AU  - Small, Kenneth A.
AU  - Winston, Clifford
AU  - Yan, Jia
Y1  - 2005/07/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2005.00619.x
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1367
EP  - 1382
VL  - 73
IS  - 4
KW  - Mixed logit
KW  - stated preference
KW  - congestion pricing
KW  - product differentiation
KW  - value of time
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2005.00619.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We apply recent econometric advances to study the distribution of commuters' preferences for speedy and reliable highway travel. Our analysis applies mixed logit to combined revealed and stated preference data on commuter choices of whether to pay a toll for congestion-free express travel. We find that motorists exhibit high values of travel time and reliability, and substantial heterogeneity in those values. We suggest that road pricing policies designed to cater to such varying preferences can improve efficiency and reduce the disparity of welfare impacts compared with recent pricing experiments.
ER  - 

